Lesson: Public vs Open & Overriding
When building frameworks or libraries, you use 'public' and 'open' to define how other modules interact with your code. 

Key Differences:
1. 'public': Accessible from any module. You can use the type and call its methods, but you cannot subclass a public class or override its methods outside its own module.
2. 'open': The most permissive level. It allows other modules to subclass the class AND override its 'open' methods.

Overriding:
When a subclass wants to provide its own implementation of a method from its parent, it uses the 'override' keyword. This tells the compiler that the change is intentional.

Example:
    open class Base { open func run() { print("Base") } }
    class Child: Base { 
        override func run() { print("Child") } 
    }

Note: 'open' only applies to classes. Structs cannot be open because they do not support inheritance.

