lesson:
Lesson: Property Observers
Property observers observe and respond to changes in a property's value. They are called every time a property's value is set, even if the new value is the same as the current value.

Core Concepts:
1. willSet: Executed just before the value is stored. Swift provides the incoming value as a constant named `newValue`.
2. didSet: Executed immediately after the new value is stored. Swift provides the previous value as a constant named `oldValue`.
3. Side Effects: These are perfect for triggering updates in other parts of the system when a specific property changes.

Example:
    var status: String = "Idle" {
        willSet { print("Changing to \(newValue)") }
        didSet { print("Changed from \(oldValue)") }
    }

Note: Property observers are NOT called when a property is first initialized in an `init`. They are only triggered by assignments made after the instance is fully initialized.

solution:
struct Gauge {
    var pressure: Int {
        willSet {
            print("Will set to \(newValue)")
        }
        didSet {
            print("Did set from \(oldValue)")
        }
    }
}

var gauge = Gauge(pressure: 1)
gauge.pressure = 3

